WEBVTT

00:02.580 --> 00:04.580
Oliver, could you help
with the bags?
No can do,

00:04.580 --> 00:07.210
big ballet audition coming up.
Can't risk an injury.

00:07.210 --> 00:08.920
I can guarantee you
an injury

00:08.920 --> 00:10.380
if you don't bring in
this damn bag.

00:10.380 --> 00:12.380
[ Trunk closes ]

00:12.380 --> 00:14.380
Are we really gonna let
Oliver go off to that
ballet boarding school?

00:14.380 --> 00:16.080
[ Sighs ]
I don't know.

00:16.080 --> 00:18.540
We've really been
kicking the can down
the road on this one.

00:18.540 --> 00:20.790
Now we're
all out of road.
I guess there's
only one thing we can do.

00:20.790 --> 00:22.920
Tonya Harding him?
What?! No.

00:22.920 --> 00:24.830
Let him audition and support him
no matter what happens.

00:24.830 --> 00:27.540
We definitely have different
parenting styles.

00:27.540 --> 00:29.250
[ Alarm beeping ]

00:29.250 --> 00:30.670
What's the code
for the new alarm?

00:30.670 --> 00:34.000
The same code we use for
everything -- 4673.

00:34.000 --> 00:35.880
[ Buttons beeping, dings ]
Why did we even get an alarm?

00:35.880 --> 00:38.710
Are we afraid someone's gonna
break in and steal our poverty?

00:38.710 --> 00:41.250
Well, it's interesting.
The landlord installed it
to lower our insurance --

00:41.250 --> 00:42.750
Huh, turns out
I don't care.

00:43.880 --> 00:46.170
Where did 4673 come from?

00:46.170 --> 00:47.920
It was your Dad's code
when we were dating,

00:47.920 --> 00:50.580
and then after we got married,
I started using it for my pin,

00:50.580 --> 00:52.540
and now it's code
to everything in our lives.

00:52.540 --> 00:54.290
But what does it mean?
I don't know.

00:54.290 --> 00:55.830
I always thought
it was just a bunch of numbers.

00:55.830 --> 00:58.500
Greg, what does 4673 mean?

00:58.500 --> 01:00.250
Katie: Was that his
"I'm caught" face?

01:00.250 --> 01:02.290
It stands for
April 6th, 1773,

01:02.290 --> 01:03.670
the day of
the Boston Tea Party.

01:03.670 --> 01:04.880
That's not right.

01:04.880 --> 01:08.250
The Boston Tea Party
was December 16th, 1773.

01:08.250 --> 01:09.960
Oh, look, toothpaste.

01:09.960 --> 01:11.830
I better put it away
before it melts.
Mm.

01:13.460 --> 01:15.710
He's clearly hiding something
about that code,

01:15.710 --> 01:17.880
and I'm gonna find out what
because in this house,

01:17.880 --> 01:18.920
only I can have secrets.

01:23.170 --> 01:27.420
♪♪

01:27.420 --> 01:30.170
♪ But a hell of a lot
to get outta skid ♪

01:30.170 --> 01:33.170
♪ People tell me
there's not a way outta skid ♪

01:33.170 --> 01:37.750
♪ But believe me, I gotta get
outta skid row ♪

01:37.750 --> 01:39.040
[ Applause ]

01:39.040 --> 01:40.620
You guys
sound great together.

01:40.620 --> 01:41.790
It's all Taylor.

01:41.790 --> 01:43.380
She is amazing.

01:43.380 --> 01:46.210
You should be playing Audrey,
not stuck as Plant Bud #3.

01:46.210 --> 01:47.960
So, what's
this play about?

01:47.960 --> 01:49.710
Oh, Pierce plays Seymour,

01:49.710 --> 01:51.830
who is madly in love
with Audrey,

01:51.830 --> 01:54.170
and he will do anything he can
to be with her,

01:54.170 --> 01:56.080
even getting rid
of her boyfriend

01:56.080 --> 01:57.750
by feeding him
to a killer plant.

01:57.750 --> 02:01.120
♪♪

02:01.120 --> 02:04.120
[ Chuckles ] Audrey's boyfriend
must be such a dope!

02:04.120 --> 02:05.790
[ Chuckles ]
If that were me,

02:05.790 --> 02:08.830
I'd be like, "Dude! Stop hanging
out with my girlfriend!"

02:11.380 --> 02:13.460
Alright, you guys,
I'll see you guys later.

02:13.460 --> 02:15.670
You guys
have great chemistry.

02:15.670 --> 02:16.880
[ Chuckles nervously ]

02:18.380 --> 02:19.750
Grandma...

02:19.750 --> 02:21.210
you want to play Pandemic?

02:21.210 --> 02:22.620
It's so fun.

02:22.620 --> 02:25.330
We have to work together to find
a cure for a disease

02:25.330 --> 02:27.750
before it destroys the world.

02:27.750 --> 02:28.620
I'll pass.

02:33.040 --> 02:34.290
What are you doing?

02:34.290 --> 02:35.830
She wants
to spend time with you.

02:35.830 --> 02:37.420
Well, then she should ask me
to do something

02:37.420 --> 02:38.790
I find interesting.

02:38.790 --> 02:41.170
Pushing through an Ambien
and going online shopping

02:41.170 --> 02:43.210
is not really her jam,
so you're gonna have to come up

02:43.210 --> 02:44.880
with another
way to bond with her.

02:44.880 --> 02:46.290
[ Chuckling ] Like what?

02:46.290 --> 02:48.540
I mean,
the other two I get.

02:48.540 --> 02:50.830
The blond one's pretty,
and the boy loves money,

02:50.830 --> 02:52.170
and those things
are in my wheelhouse,

02:52.170 --> 02:55.750
but Anna-Kat and I
don't really

02:55.750 --> 02:57.620
have anything in common.

02:57.620 --> 03:00.380
And besides,
I don't have time.

03:00.380 --> 03:03.000
Some delinquent has been
stealing my eye cream packages

03:03.000 --> 03:04.290
from the front steps,

03:04.290 --> 03:06.620
so now I have to sit here
and wait for it to come.

03:06.620 --> 03:09.420
I know what you guys
could do together.

03:09.420 --> 03:12.330
You could have a stakeout to see
who's stealing the eye cream.

03:12.330 --> 03:15.040
Yeah, we can use the new
doorbell cam

03:15.040 --> 03:18.000
to catch us a porch burglar
with beautiful under eyes.

03:18.000 --> 03:19.830
I wou-- I would, but --

03:19.830 --> 03:21.290
That's why you're here --

03:21.290 --> 03:23.880
to spend quality time
with your grandchildren.

03:23.880 --> 03:25.460
Otherwise, I don't know,

03:25.460 --> 03:27.830
go buy a tent
and live in the woods,

03:27.830 --> 03:29.960
make margaritas
with your own urine.

03:32.330 --> 03:34.750
Stakeout it is.
Awesome!

03:36.040 --> 03:38.580
So, I was thinking,

03:38.580 --> 03:42.710
it's weird you got the date
wrong for the Boston Tea Party,

03:42.710 --> 03:45.210
being a history professor
and all.

03:45.210 --> 03:46.710
Oh, just 'cause
I'm a history professor,

03:46.710 --> 03:48.040
I'm supposed to know
all the dates?

03:48.040 --> 03:49.710
Do dancers know
all the dances?

03:49.710 --> 03:52.540
I bet Baryshnikov doesn't know
how to do the Electric Slide.

03:52.540 --> 03:56.380
Greg,
what does "4673" mean?

03:56.380 --> 03:58.330
[ Sighs ]

03:58.330 --> 04:01.000
[ Chuckles ]

04:01.000 --> 04:03.170
This interrogation
can be quick and easy,

04:03.170 --> 04:05.330
or it could last all night.

04:05.330 --> 04:07.210
You think about
how you want to play it.

04:07.210 --> 04:10.670
[ Sighs ]

04:10.670 --> 04:13.000
It spells out "hope"
on a keypad.

04:13.000 --> 04:15.420
Like, "Star Wars: A New Hope,"
"or hope springs eternal,"

04:15.420 --> 04:16.710
my favorite phrase.

04:16.710 --> 04:18.670
"Hope" that answers
your question.

04:18.670 --> 04:23.790
[ Forceful laughing ]

04:23.790 --> 04:28.000
Greg, why does it
spell "hope"?

04:28.000 --> 04:30.170
Because when I got
a bank card in college,

04:30.170 --> 04:31.920
I had a crush
on a girl named Hope.

04:31.920 --> 04:34.420
That's it.

04:35.710 --> 04:38.460
Who I then asked out...

04:38.460 --> 04:39.460
and she said yes.

04:41.920 --> 04:44.580
So we went out...

04:44.580 --> 04:46.330
and continued to do so
for two years.

04:46.330 --> 04:48.170
Two years?!
That's not that long!

04:48.170 --> 04:49.710
Don't tell me
it's not that long!

04:49.710 --> 04:52.460
For a reality star, that is
a baby, a marriage, a divorce,

04:52.460 --> 04:53.790
and a launch
of a lifestyle brand!

04:53.790 --> 04:55.120
This is why
I didn't want to tell you.

04:55.120 --> 04:56.290
Because I knew
you'd overreact.

04:56.290 --> 04:58.380
Naw, I'm cool, bruh.

04:58.380 --> 05:00.420
I'm not overreacting.

05:00.420 --> 05:02.210
You've seen me overreact.

05:04.710 --> 05:06.540
Taylor, if you don't care
enough about your shoes

05:06.540 --> 05:07.620
to put them away,

05:07.620 --> 05:09.920
then you don't deserve
to have shoes!

05:09.920 --> 05:12.210
Hi, Greg.
Hey, Katie.

05:12.210 --> 05:15.170
So how did it end between you
and this Hope woman?

05:15.170 --> 05:16.290
It doesn't matter.

05:16.290 --> 05:18.040
If it doesn't matter,
then tell me.

05:18.040 --> 05:19.460
Fine, we went out
for two years,

05:19.460 --> 05:20.790
I thought she was "the one."

05:20.790 --> 05:22.290
Then she dumped me
and broke my heart.

05:22.290 --> 05:25.000
Where is she now?
I don't know.

05:25.000 --> 05:26.290
I don't know,
and I don't care.

05:26.290 --> 05:27.830
I married you.

05:27.830 --> 05:29.250
Honey, I promise you.

05:29.250 --> 05:31.210
This code is no big deal.

05:33.960 --> 05:35.710
It is a huge deal!

05:35.710 --> 05:36.920
Huge!

05:42.710 --> 05:45.460
I can't believe Greg would even
date a girl named Hope.

05:45.460 --> 05:48.290
Ugh, It's so trashy.
Totally.

05:48.290 --> 05:50.580
Actually,
I love the name Hope.
Me, too.

05:50.580 --> 05:52.830
But who cares if we like it?
Hope's spirit is haunting

05:52.830 --> 05:54.620
every nook and cranny
of your marriage.

05:54.620 --> 05:56.330
You have to change
that code.
But you can't stop there.

05:56.330 --> 05:58.120
Mnh-mnh.
You need to send this Hope
a message.

05:58.120 --> 06:00.000
What do you mean?
Well, a few years ago,

06:00.000 --> 06:02.290
I found a mix tape
from Richard's middle
school girlfriend.

06:02.290 --> 06:03.750
I not only burned it,

06:03.750 --> 06:06.540
I then tracked the skank down,
stole her identity,

06:06.540 --> 06:09.120
and then racked up all sorts of
charges at Barney's.

06:09.120 --> 06:12.290
She won't be able to buy a house
for a very long time.

06:12.290 --> 06:13.830
Solid Plan B,

06:13.830 --> 06:16.330
but for now, I'm just gonna make
him change the code.

06:16.330 --> 06:18.500
If for no other reason
than this is the first time

06:18.500 --> 06:21.750
you two have ever agreed
on anything.
No, it's not.

06:21.750 --> 06:24.330
We've agreed
on something before.
What?

06:24.330 --> 06:26.000
That we both love
the name Hope.

06:26.000 --> 06:28.120
[ Both laugh ]
Y'all are bitches. [ Laughs ]

06:31.250 --> 06:33.620
Alright, let's do this.
Okay.

06:33.620 --> 06:34.580
[ Grunts ]

06:34.580 --> 06:36.620
[ Scoffs ] That's it.
I suck.

06:36.620 --> 06:38.330
I'm never gonna get the girls'
ballet scholarship.

06:38.330 --> 06:40.330
Have fun at Deervale
without me.

06:40.330 --> 06:41.920
Even if I do
get the boys' scholarship,

06:41.920 --> 06:43.540
I'm not going without you.

06:43.540 --> 06:45.290
Really?

06:45.290 --> 06:47.960
So, we both go
or neither of us go.

06:47.960 --> 06:49.880
Deal?
Deal.

06:49.880 --> 06:51.380
We'll practice all day.

06:51.380 --> 06:52.540
Okay, now help me
get this lift.

06:54.620 --> 06:55.380
Do it again!

06:57.460 --> 06:58.500
Do it again!

06:58.500 --> 06:59.710
[ Groans ] Do it again!

06:59.710 --> 07:07.750
♪♪

07:07.750 --> 07:10.460
We did it!
Those scholarships
are totally ours.

07:10.460 --> 07:11.920
Thanks for not
giving up on me.

07:11.920 --> 07:13.080
We're in this together.

07:16.460 --> 07:18.380
Don't do it again!

07:18.380 --> 07:19.290
Yes, sir.

07:21.330 --> 07:22.540
Oh, hey, Oliver.

07:22.540 --> 07:24.210
How was ballet practice?

07:24.210 --> 07:26.710
Great.
Gina and I got our move down.

07:26.710 --> 07:28.080
Was it this move?

07:29.790 --> 07:32.040
[ Whispering ] Gina...

07:32.040 --> 07:34.170
Were you pervs spying on me
through the window?

07:34.170 --> 07:36.710
We're not some creepy
peeping toms.

07:36.710 --> 07:38.250
We watched you
on the doorbell cam.

07:38.250 --> 07:41.790
[ Sighs ] I can't wait
to get out of this place.

07:41.790 --> 07:44.880
Awfully uptight for a guy
who just got to first base.

07:44.880 --> 07:46.420
[ Bells chiming ]
Alright, what do we got?

07:46.420 --> 07:50.420
Taylor: [ Laughs ] Shut up!
I am not!

07:50.420 --> 07:51.920
Is that Trip?

07:51.920 --> 07:53.710
Tell him...
[deep voice] "wassup"...

07:53.710 --> 07:55.580
[normal voice] like that.
Wassup?

07:55.580 --> 07:57.380
Um, it's not Trip.
It's Pierce.

07:57.380 --> 07:58.580
Hey, Mr. Otto!

07:58.580 --> 07:59.620
Oh.

07:59.620 --> 08:01.000
Pierce.

08:01.000 --> 08:02.210
Is everything okay,
Mr. Otto?

08:02.210 --> 08:03.500
Yeah.

08:03.500 --> 08:04.880
All good.

08:04.880 --> 08:06.540
Very disappointed about
something else.

08:08.710 --> 08:11.000
Taylor's on the phone giggling
with a boy other than Trip.

08:11.000 --> 08:12.040
Pierce?

08:12.040 --> 08:13.500
Yeah.

08:13.500 --> 08:15.330
Trip is nice,
respectful.

08:15.330 --> 08:17.000
Sure, he pronounces spaghetti
"basketti,"

08:17.000 --> 08:18.210
but he's basically
everything I want

08:18.210 --> 08:19.750
for Taylor's
high school boyfriend.

08:19.750 --> 08:22.420
This Pierce kid, he's sneaky.
I don't like him.

08:22.420 --> 08:23.920
Well, you better be careful,

08:23.920 --> 08:27.960
or she'll end up using Pierce's
name for a code or something.

08:29.380 --> 08:31.210
We're still here?
We never left.

08:31.210 --> 08:32.580
I want you
to change that code.

08:32.580 --> 08:35.250
It's just a code!
A code that means Hope!

08:35.250 --> 08:36.960
And Hope
is not good, Greg!

08:36.960 --> 08:38.420
There will be no Hope
in this house.

08:38.420 --> 08:40.250
It used to mean Hope.
Now it means 4673,

08:40.250 --> 08:42.750
the series of numbers I use
whenever I need a code.
That is my point.

08:42.750 --> 08:45.380
We use it all the time,
and every time we do, Hope,

08:45.380 --> 08:46.670
the girl who you'd be with
right now

08:46.670 --> 08:48.460
if she hadn't dumped you,
is there.

08:48.460 --> 08:50.710
Katie.
We use that code
for our ATMs,

08:50.710 --> 08:52.710
for our phones,
for our motel safes.

08:52.710 --> 08:54.500
Hope has been
on every vacation with us.

08:54.500 --> 08:56.620
I want it changed.

08:56.620 --> 09:00.250
Katie, do you have any idea how
hard it would be to change

09:00.250 --> 09:03.250
every code, pin number,
and password we've created
over the last 20 years?

09:03.250 --> 09:05.580
You're being crazy!
Don't call me crazy

09:05.580 --> 09:08.210
for not wanting another woman
in our relationship.

09:08.210 --> 09:09.420
Fine, not crazy --
Jealous.

09:09.420 --> 09:11.420
You're being jealous
over nothing!

09:11.420 --> 09:14.710
You mean to tell me
that you wouldn't be jealous

09:14.710 --> 09:17.000
if I was parading around
mementos

09:17.000 --> 09:19.830
from my past relationships
in front of you?

09:19.830 --> 09:22.210
Yes, because we are
happily married.

09:25.420 --> 09:27.170
Good to know.

09:28.540 --> 09:30.380
[ Screams ]
[ Laughs ]

09:30.380 --> 09:33.540
And another kid
crashes his scooter.

09:33.540 --> 09:35.460
I told you when we put that
stick in the middle of the road

09:35.460 --> 09:37.210
we'd see some action.

09:37.210 --> 09:38.750
You owe me a dollar.
Oh, come on.

09:38.750 --> 09:39.920
All right,
you can keep your dollar

09:39.920 --> 09:42.500
if you get me some more ice
for my G&T.

09:42.500 --> 09:46.790
Just use some
of my frozen grapes.

09:46.790 --> 09:49.210
They keep the drink cold
without watering it down.

09:49.210 --> 09:50.790
Whoa. Whoa, whoa, whoa.

09:50.790 --> 09:53.460
I feel like I just had
my very first 'Lude.

09:53.460 --> 09:56.330
Mama used to try
and dilute my juice with ice,

09:56.330 --> 09:58.250
but I was onto
her little game.

09:58.250 --> 09:59.420
If you ever work in a bar,

09:59.420 --> 10:01.500
this should be
your signature move.

10:01.500 --> 10:03.210
You know, you wouldn't even have
to flirt with married men

10:03.210 --> 10:04.750
while their wives
are in the bathroom.

10:04.750 --> 10:06.830
You could just throw a couple
of those grapes in their drinks,

10:06.830 --> 10:08.920
and watch those tips
come pouring in!

10:08.920 --> 10:10.960
I can't work at a bar.

10:10.960 --> 10:13.080
I spill every time
I walk with a drink.

10:13.080 --> 10:14.960
Oh, I can help you
with that.

10:14.960 --> 10:16.960
Really?
Honey...

10:16.960 --> 10:20.210
I could carry a martini
in high-altitude turbulence

10:20.210 --> 10:22.120
while Richard Dawson
slapped my ass

10:22.120 --> 10:24.540
without spilling a drop.
[ Chuckles ]

10:24.540 --> 10:26.000
Grandma...

10:26.000 --> 10:27.920
I love how you don't know
how to talk to children.

10:27.920 --> 10:29.710
Oh, thanks.

10:32.080 --> 10:33.830
Do you know where
my reading glasses are?

10:33.830 --> 10:35.170
What's that?

10:35.170 --> 10:36.880
You like my sweatshirt?

10:36.880 --> 10:38.580
Oh, I forgot
I had it on.

10:38.580 --> 10:41.120
You're probably wondering
where I even got it.

10:41.120 --> 10:42.710
Not really.

10:42.710 --> 10:44.750
Acapulco,
Spring Break '98.

10:44.750 --> 10:47.210
The weather was hot,
and I was hotter.

10:47.210 --> 10:48.670
All right,
I'll find them myself.

10:48.670 --> 10:51.120
It wasn't long until a former
"Real World" cast member

10:51.120 --> 10:52.620
noticed me.

10:52.620 --> 10:55.500
We spent three days
on the beach together,

10:55.500 --> 10:58.830
listening to Usher's
"Nice and Slow" on repeat,

10:58.830 --> 11:00.710
which is appropriate

11:00.710 --> 11:03.330
'cause that's how
I remember our time together --

11:03.330 --> 11:08.540
nice and slow.

11:08.540 --> 11:10.080
I for one loved that story.

11:10.080 --> 11:12.380
I think you look great
in this hoodie.

11:12.380 --> 11:14.000
Okay, cool, thanks.

11:14.000 --> 11:20.420
♪♪

11:20.420 --> 11:26.580
♪♪

11:26.580 --> 11:28.120
Hey!

11:28.120 --> 11:29.710
Oh, sorry.

11:29.710 --> 11:32.120
I just want to do a little
reminiscing before bed.

11:32.120 --> 11:33.580
[ Gasps ]

11:33.580 --> 11:35.920
My high school boyfriend's
football jersey.

11:35.920 --> 11:37.120
Remind me.

11:37.120 --> 11:38.420
Did you play football,
Greg?

11:38.420 --> 11:39.670
I did not.

11:39.670 --> 11:42.170
Oh, that's right.

11:42.170 --> 11:44.170
[ Gasps ]
Oh, look at these sweatpants.

11:44.170 --> 11:46.120
This guy was much taller
than me,

11:46.120 --> 11:48.920
so when I wore them,
we would just laugh and laugh

11:48.920 --> 11:50.750
and cuddle and laugh.

11:50.750 --> 11:51.920
Sounds fun.

11:51.920 --> 11:54.790
Aww, my old jewelry box!

11:54.790 --> 11:57.500
It is gonna take quite a while
to sort through all of this

11:57.500 --> 12:00.120
and piece together
who gave me what.

12:00.120 --> 12:01.920
Be a doll and grab
a pen and paper.

12:01.920 --> 12:03.040
No.

12:03.040 --> 12:04.580
Why not?

12:04.580 --> 12:06.580
Is there
something wrong, Greg?

12:06.580 --> 12:07.750
Is there?

12:07.750 --> 12:10.580
I cannot believe
you kept all of this stuff!

12:10.580 --> 12:12.040
And there's
so much of it!

12:12.040 --> 12:13.750
How could you even care
about my one thing

12:13.750 --> 12:15.040
when you've got
all these things?!

12:15.040 --> 12:17.170
Because holding onto one thing
means a lot more

12:17.170 --> 12:19.040
than a box
of random crap.

12:19.040 --> 12:21.540
You type in Hope's name
every day.

12:21.540 --> 12:23.620
I don't even remember
some of these guys' names.

12:23.620 --> 12:25.380
That's supposed
to make me feel better?!

12:25.380 --> 12:27.420
I'm definitely
not changing the code now.

12:27.420 --> 12:30.040
Well, I'm definitely not
sleeping in the same bed
with you tonight!

12:30.040 --> 12:32.120
Smart! Seems like you've got
enough men here

12:32.120 --> 12:34.170
to keep you warm anyway!
I'm gonna go sleep on the couch!

12:34.170 --> 12:35.880
No, you won't!
The couch hurts your back!

12:35.880 --> 12:37.420
I'll sleep on the couch!

12:37.420 --> 12:39.120
Thank you!

12:45.290 --> 12:47.540
My, my,
if these shells could talk.

12:52.250 --> 12:54.000
Did you put a lock
on the refrigerator?

12:54.000 --> 12:55.330
Sure did.
Why?

12:55.330 --> 12:57.380
[ Knock on door ]
No reason,

12:57.380 --> 12:59.000
but if you need anything,
you know the code.

12:59.000 --> 13:01.670
[ Inhales sharply ]

13:01.670 --> 13:03.540
Hey, Mr. A.
Hey.

13:03.540 --> 13:05.880
Whoa, sweet lid,
Mrs. A.

13:05.880 --> 13:07.460
Thank you.

13:07.460 --> 13:09.250
I spent a lot of time
at this fraternity house.

13:09.250 --> 13:11.250
What were we doing?
Good question, Trip.

13:11.250 --> 13:13.960
Not homework,
I can tell you that.

13:13.960 --> 13:15.460
So what brings you here,
Trip?

13:15.460 --> 13:17.960
Your daughter, Taylor.
We're dating.

13:17.960 --> 13:21.540
Yes, I know, but she's running
lines with Pierce at school.

13:21.540 --> 13:23.920
Hmm, that's weird.

13:23.920 --> 13:26.120
Pierce told me they weren't
rehearsing today.

13:26.120 --> 13:27.960
Ah, must be
an honest mistake.

13:27.960 --> 13:30.170
Have a good one.
Trip, sit down.

13:33.380 --> 13:34.790
We like you.

13:34.790 --> 13:36.540
So much.

13:36.540 --> 13:38.710
Which is why we need to have
this talk.

13:38.710 --> 13:40.210
Do you know why
Pierce told you

13:40.210 --> 13:41.380
that there
was no rehearsal today?

13:44.040 --> 13:45.670
Trip,
did you hear Mrs. A?

13:45.670 --> 13:47.670
Yeah, yeah, but when someone
asks me a super hard question,

13:47.670 --> 13:49.420
if I just smile,
they usually tell me the answer.

13:49.420 --> 13:50.580
Ah.

13:50.580 --> 13:52.620
Here it is.

13:52.620 --> 13:54.750
Pierce is trying
to steal Taylor from you.

13:54.750 --> 13:56.670
[ Laughs ] No.

13:56.670 --> 13:58.460
They're just friends.
Not if he can help it.

13:58.460 --> 14:00.210
He calls Taylor at night,
makes her giggle.

14:00.210 --> 14:02.420
He's always complimenting her,
and last week,

14:02.420 --> 14:05.460
I saw him touch her arm
like this.

14:05.460 --> 14:08.250
Greg, you could've used me
as the example.
Oh.

14:08.250 --> 14:09.380
I'm going down there.

14:09.380 --> 14:11.500
Wait.

14:11.500 --> 14:14.460
For luck.

14:14.460 --> 14:16.790
Last guy who had them
certainly got lucky.

14:16.790 --> 14:19.170
[ Car horn blares ]

14:19.170 --> 14:20.540
Gina's parents are here.

14:20.540 --> 14:22.080
They're taking me
to the ballet audition.

14:23.920 --> 14:26.750
Why is there a lock
on the fridge?

14:26.750 --> 14:29.000
And what are you wearing?

14:29.000 --> 14:31.250
[ Scoffs ] Boarding school
can't come fast enough.

14:31.250 --> 14:33.080
Hey, come here.

14:36.710 --> 14:38.880
Good luck today.

14:38.880 --> 14:40.670
I hope you get it.

14:40.670 --> 14:42.330
Even though it's gonna be hard
just seeing you

14:42.330 --> 14:44.210
during the summer, Thanksgiving,
and Christmas.

14:44.210 --> 14:45.670
[ Chuckles ]
Just Christmas.

14:51.120 --> 14:52.540
I want him
to follow his dreams,

14:52.540 --> 14:54.880
but I am not ready
for him to leave.

14:54.880 --> 14:56.120
I feel the same way.

14:56.120 --> 14:57.080
I don't know
what to hope for.

14:57.080 --> 14:58.710
"Hope"?

14:58.710 --> 15:00.000
Really, Greg?

15:00.000 --> 15:02.040
That's the word you choose?
Wha--

15:04.250 --> 15:05.290
Oh, come on.

15:05.290 --> 15:08.080
It was an accident!

15:08.080 --> 15:09.210
It wasn't.

15:12.120 --> 15:14.920
Thank you all
for your efforts.

15:14.920 --> 15:18.540
Our female
scholarship recipient is...

15:18.540 --> 15:21.460
Gina Tuscadero.
[ Gasping ]

15:21.460 --> 15:22.750
Oh, my God, we did it!

15:22.750 --> 15:24.000
We're going to Deervale.

15:24.000 --> 15:26.830
And our male scholarship
winner is...

15:26.830 --> 15:28.080
Andrew Vandevorde!

15:28.080 --> 15:30.000
Ha, ha, yes!

15:30.000 --> 15:32.250
They totally mispronounced
my name!

15:32.250 --> 15:34.580
♪ Sweet understanding ♪

15:34.580 --> 15:36.710
♪ Sweet understanding ♪

15:36.710 --> 15:38.670
♪ Sweet understanding ♪

15:38.670 --> 15:40.580
♪ Sweet understanding ♪

15:40.580 --> 15:44.540
[ Together ]
♪ Sweet understanding ♪

15:44.540 --> 15:52.790
♪ Seymour's my man ♪
♪ Seymour's your man ♪

15:52.790 --> 15:55.710
[ Door slams open ]
Step away from my girl!

15:55.710 --> 15:58.790
Trip?
Whoa, we're just rehearsing.

15:58.790 --> 16:00.500
Yeah, calm down.
Nothing's going on.

16:00.500 --> 16:03.210
He's trying to steal you
away from me.
What?

16:03.210 --> 16:04.880
Think about it --
the compliments,

16:04.880 --> 16:06.580
the extra rehearsal time,

16:06.580 --> 16:08.710
he even caresses your arm
like your dad did to me.

16:08.710 --> 16:10.830
I'm just helping her become
the understudy for Audrey.

16:10.830 --> 16:12.540
You're way too good
to be in the chorus.

16:12.540 --> 16:14.380
See?
That's a compliment!

16:14.380 --> 16:16.540
He's all over you
like meat sauce on bisketti.

16:16.540 --> 16:18.210
You have to quit the play,
Taylor.

16:18.210 --> 16:19.920
Look, I don't want to get
in the middle of this.

16:19.920 --> 16:21.330
You do whatever you want,

16:21.330 --> 16:23.290
but quitting the play
would be a big mistake, Tay.

16:23.290 --> 16:25.290
Tay?!
You don't call her Tay!

16:25.290 --> 16:27.380
I call her Tay!

16:27.380 --> 16:28.750
Even though
I never call her Tay.

16:28.750 --> 16:30.710
Whoa, he's just acting
like a friend,

16:30.710 --> 16:32.620
and you're acting
like a controlling jerk.

16:32.620 --> 16:34.000
Taylor...

16:34.000 --> 16:35.670
I'm not gonna sit
in the audience

16:35.670 --> 16:37.830
and watch some guy
steal my girlfriend.

16:37.830 --> 16:40.330
You're quitting.
I'm doing the play.

16:40.330 --> 16:42.210
So you don't have to worry
about some guy

16:42.210 --> 16:44.920
trying to steal
your girlfriend...

16:44.920 --> 16:46.380
because you don't have one
anymore.

16:50.620 --> 16:52.830
♪♪

16:52.830 --> 16:54.170
Are you okay?

16:54.170 --> 17:01.460
♪♪

17:01.460 --> 17:04.620
Oh, you are a natural
stewardess.

17:04.620 --> 17:05.620
[ Both chuckle ]

17:05.620 --> 17:06.920
Oh, I bet you'd be great

17:06.920 --> 17:09.750
at slamming into people's elbows
with a drink cart.

17:09.750 --> 17:11.750
[ Bells chime ]

17:11.750 --> 17:13.540
Oh, look, Grandma.

17:13.540 --> 17:15.000
It's your eye cream
delivery.

17:15.000 --> 17:16.170
I'll go get it.

17:16.170 --> 17:17.460
Ooh, not yet.

17:17.460 --> 17:19.210
Let's leave it as bait.

17:19.210 --> 17:20.920
Then we can see
who's been taking it.

17:20.920 --> 17:24.290
And besides,
I'm not in any big rush.

17:24.290 --> 17:26.000
Spending time with you
has been nice.

17:37.960 --> 17:39.920
My eye cream.
Where --

17:39.920 --> 17:42.420
Where did that come from?

17:42.420 --> 17:44.750
I'm the thief.
Ah.

17:44.750 --> 17:46.790
I stole them
because I was mad at you

17:46.790 --> 17:49.710
for never wanting
to play with me.

17:49.710 --> 17:51.750
I'm really,
really sorry, but...

17:51.750 --> 17:54.460
I --
[ Chuckles ]

17:54.460 --> 17:56.710
I'm also really, really happy
we did this stakeout.

17:59.710 --> 18:00.960
[ Quietly ] Come here.

18:05.710 --> 18:07.620
I love you, Grandma.

18:07.620 --> 18:10.880
Oh, and I love you, too,
honey.

18:10.880 --> 18:12.080
Oh, my God.

18:12.080 --> 18:13.120
I really do.

18:15.830 --> 18:17.580
Oliver: [ Sighs ] I'm sorry
I messed this up for us.

18:17.580 --> 18:19.120
I'll audition again
next year.

18:19.120 --> 18:20.670
Oliver...

18:20.670 --> 18:22.170
I'm taking
the scholarship.

18:22.170 --> 18:24.290
What?!
What about our pact?

18:24.290 --> 18:26.330
We both go
or neither of us go, right?

18:26.330 --> 18:29.040
I can't pass up
this opportunity.

18:29.040 --> 18:31.000
If the roles were reversed,
you would do the same thing.

18:31.000 --> 18:33.080
No, I wouldn't.

18:33.080 --> 18:34.880
Oh, that's sweet.
[ Chuckles ]

18:34.880 --> 18:36.580
But I'm still gonna go.

18:36.580 --> 18:38.210
I'm sorry.

18:38.210 --> 18:40.210
I hope one day
you'll understand.

18:41.710 --> 18:48.420
♪♪

18:48.420 --> 18:50.790
The doorbell cam. Hmm.

18:50.790 --> 18:52.880
Can make you laugh,

18:52.880 --> 18:55.040
can make you cry.

18:55.040 --> 19:00.250
♪♪

19:00.250 --> 19:03.250
Hey.
We heard you were out here.

19:03.250 --> 19:05.500
The doorbell girls filled us in
on what happened.

19:05.500 --> 19:07.120
We're sorry you didn't get
the scholarship,

19:07.120 --> 19:08.420
and that Gina --
Tore my heart out

19:08.420 --> 19:09.790
and stomped it
on the ground?

19:09.790 --> 19:12.330
Oh, honey.

19:12.330 --> 19:14.880
This sucks.
I know it does,

19:14.880 --> 19:17.040
but this is the first
of what's likely to be
several relationships

19:17.040 --> 19:20.080
that come and go over
the years on your path
to finding the one.

19:20.080 --> 19:22.000
It may not
seem like it now, but...

19:22.000 --> 19:24.170
you'll find
your person someday.

19:24.170 --> 19:27.250
You will,
and Gina will just be a girl

19:27.250 --> 19:30.580
who gave you some random gift
you forgot you even had.

19:32.210 --> 19:35.380
Gina never gave me --

19:35.380 --> 19:36.960
What are you guys doing?

19:36.960 --> 19:38.830
Is this for you or for me?
For you, for you.

19:38.830 --> 19:40.210
Yeah, we'll give you
some space.

19:40.210 --> 19:44.750
No. You stay. I'll go.

19:44.750 --> 19:46.120
That's what she said.

19:50.000 --> 19:52.170
I'm sorry.
I was being stupid.

19:52.170 --> 19:54.120
This is what's important --
our kids, our family,

19:54.120 --> 19:56.080
the life we built.
Everything else is just --

19:56.080 --> 19:57.580
Nonsense.

19:57.580 --> 19:59.040
'Cause when
you get married,

19:59.040 --> 20:01.670
you start
a new life together.

20:01.670 --> 20:03.580
I love you.
I love you, too.

20:06.420 --> 20:08.330
But I still need
that code changed.

20:08.330 --> 20:10.460
And you'll get rid of the stuff
from your old boyfriends?
Yep.

20:10.460 --> 20:13.830
Just help me get the rest of
the boxes out of the basement.

20:13.830 --> 20:15.170
There's more?!

20:18.040 --> 20:19.580
Oliver...

20:19.580 --> 20:22.170
I know you are sad about Gina
and the boarding school,

20:22.170 --> 20:23.790
but look on the bright side.

20:23.790 --> 20:26.250
You get to stay here
with us!

20:27.580 --> 20:29.670
You suck
at silver linings, Mom.

20:29.670 --> 20:30.960
Thank you.

20:30.960 --> 20:33.790
And honey, I'm so sorry
that you and Trip broke up,

20:33.790 --> 20:36.670
but I am proud of you
for being a strong woman

20:36.670 --> 20:39.210
and putting
your own interests first.

20:39.210 --> 20:41.420
You should feel good
about yourself.

20:41.420 --> 20:42.880
Yeah, I guess.

20:42.880 --> 20:45.170
I still want to throw up every
time I think about it.

20:45.170 --> 20:46.500
Mm...

20:46.500 --> 20:48.210
But at least
I'm doing better than Dad.

20:48.210 --> 20:49.580
Oh, Trip.

20:49.580 --> 20:51.330
I just feel so blindsided.

20:51.330 --> 20:54.290
♪♪

21:01.620 --> 21:03.420
[ Door opens ]

21:03.420 --> 21:05.170
The security company
called me today.

21:05.170 --> 21:07.120
What happened
with the alarm?
I can't remember
the new code.

21:07.120 --> 21:09.290
We have to go back
to 4673,

21:09.290 --> 21:11.620
but it needs to mean
something else.

21:14.710 --> 21:17.250
Well, it also spells
H-O-R-E --

21:17.250 --> 21:18.290
"Hore."

21:18.290 --> 21:19.670
Perfect!

21:19.670 --> 21:20.880
"Hore" it is.
